    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Return Run with Walk Breaks\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with a brisk 3-minute walk to warm up the foot and ankle. Focus on gentle heel-to-toe rolling motion. Stop if you feel any sharp pain in the right foot.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at a fully conversational easy pace (5:58/km). If any foot discomfort arises, immediately drop to a walk for 1-2 minutes before resuming. Keep effort very low — you should be able to speak in full sentences throughout.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk the final 3 minutes. After stopping, perform gentle calf stretches and plantar fascia stretches as directed by your physiotherapist.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Walk briskly for 3 minutes before beginning any running. This is non-negotiable with active plantar fasciitis — the foot needs time to warm up and loosen before load is applied.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for at least 3 minutes after finishing. Stretch calves, Achilles, and the plantar fascia gently. Apply ice to the right heel for 10-15 minutes if any soreness is present post-run.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"James, this is your Monday session — a gentle, controlled easy run to keep momentum going from your recent positive training history. Your last few runs have been encouraging, especially the 20-minute effort on March 19 with no reported pain. We are keeping duration capped at 20 minutes as per your physio clearance. The pace target is 5:58/km — the conservative end of your easy range — to minimise ground reaction force on the right foot. Walk breaks are always available and should be used proactively at any sign of foot discomfort. Do not push through pain. This week's total volume is modest and intentional.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Midweek Easy Run — Foot Check\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3-minute walk warmup. Pay close attention to how the right foot feels during these first few minutes. Morning stiffness is common with plantar fasciitis — do not rush into running.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy conversational running at 5:58/km. This is your midweek check-in run. Use it to assess how the foot is responding to Monday's session. If Monday caused any lingering soreness, reduce this to a 15-minute run-walk and note it for your physio.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk cooldown for 3 minutes. Perform your prescribed foot and calf mobility work immediately after.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Walk for 3 minutes before running. If the foot feels stiff or sore from Monday, extend the walk warmup to 5 minutes or convert the entire session to a 20-minute walk — that is still a productive training stimulus at this stage.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk cooldown, calf stretches, plantar fascia stretch. Ice if needed. Log your foot pain level (0-10) after every run so you and your physio have clear data.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Thursday gives you 72 hours of recovery from Monday, which is ideal for managing plantar fasciitis. This session mirrors Monday in structure and intent. Think of it as a data-gathering run as much as a fitness run — you are learning how your foot responds to back-to-back training weeks. If you notice a pattern of stiffness in the first 5 minutes that resolves (as happened on March 10), that is generally acceptable. Sharp or worsening pain is a signal to stop and contact your physiotherapist. No speed work, no hills, no pushing the pace.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Weekend Long Run — Easy and Controlled\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk warmup for 3 minutes. This is your longest effort of the week — take the warmup seriously. Loosen up the ankles and calves with gentle circles before you begin walking.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy running at 5:58/km. Even though this is labelled the long run, the duration cap of 20 minutes applies per your physio clearance. The distinction from your other runs is psychological and structural — Saturday is your anchor session each week. Focus on smooth, relaxed form: short stride, low heel drop, relaxed shoulders.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk for 3 minutes. This is the end of your training week — take extra time with your post-run routine. Stretch, roll, and rest well into Sunday.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3-minute walk warmup minimum. On Saturday mornings, the foot may be stiffer after a week of activity. Give it the time it needs. There is no rush.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Extended cooldown walk of 5 minutes if possible. Full stretching routine for calves, Achilles, hip flexors, and plantar fascia. Consider a contrast foot soak (warm then cool water) if recommended by your physio. Rest completely on Sunday.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday is your long run anchor, James, and we are honouring that structure even within the constraints of your injury rehab. At this stage, all three of your weekly runs are capped at 20 minutes per your physiotherapist's clearance, so the long run is differentiated by its role in your weekly rhythm rather than its duration. As you progress and your physio clears you for longer efforts, Saturday will be the first session we extend. This week's total volume across three sessions is approximately 10 km — consistent with your recent training history and within safe progression limits. No speed work of any kind until you receive explicit clearance. Your VDOT of 46.5 reflects your pre-injury fitness; right now, the only goal is healthy, consistent running. Fitness will return quickly once the foot is fully settled. You are doing the right things — keep it steady.\",\"perceived_effort\":3}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "modelId": "\"claude-sonnet-4-6\"",
